postcontent:
Smith & Wesson model 60-9. It's a pre-lock, meaning it doesn't have that ugly key hole lock seen on newer models. It's .38 Special, also rated for .38+P. Manufacture date was 1996. The trigger pull on this one is just amazing. Really smooth. You'll have to dry fire it to see for yourself.

If ad is up it means it's still for sale. God bless!

vz.58 Military
Imported from Czechoslovakia and manufactured D-Technic.

Advantages of Sa vz. 58 over AK47 rifles (cited from Richard Rich Chris)
- All vz. 58 rifles possess a milled receiver; the vast majority of AK47s utilize stamped sheet metal receivers and are not as rigid as the vz.58 receiver.
- Even with the milled receiver it is almost one pound lighter than a stamped AK47.
- The bolt of the vz. 58 stays open after the last round in the magazine has been fired â€“ the shooter immediately knows the firearm is empty and allows for quicker reloads.
- The vz. 58 can be reloaded with stripper clips while the magazine is inserted in the rifle.
- The vz. 58 has a more natural point of aim and is faster handling.
- The safety is more ergonomic making a faster first shot possible with the vz. 58. Unlike the AK safety, the vz. 58 safety can be operated by just a forefinger with the hand remaining on the pistol grip.
- vz.58 has no need for an ejection port dust cover as the receiver is completely enclosed. A cover (on the safety lever) must be used on the AK47 to prevent debris from entering the receiver through the reciprocating charging handle slot.
- The ejection port is HUGE. There is no chance of an empty case getting stuck in the action of the vz. 58.
- The vz. 58 gas piston can be removed or exchanged without tools.
- The alloy magazine of the vz. 58 is half the weight of the steel AK47 magazine.
- The vz. 58 is striker fired unlike the hammer fired AK47. This reduces the number of parts and possible points of failure.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Lake Geneva Walmart .22lr
postcontent:
Was at Walmart in Lake Geneva last night with my wife, saw some interesting things. They had gotten a shipment of ammo in, and there was a line waiting to buy whatever came out. As I was also waiting, I overheard quite a few people in the front of the line calling the salesman "Uncle Steve", or just Steve. Seemed strange, but I paid it no mind. After listening a bit more, I realized the first 10 people in line were Steve's family members. They each bought 6 boxes of .22lr(limit is 3), including 1000 round packs for $48. The 9mm was gone before I got to the front of the line. "Steve" was paying for it out of his pocket, I overheard one woman saying how much money they were going to make online. "Thanks Uncle Steve!" was heard several times. My wife and I managed to get 6 boxes, the last 6 boxes. 

This guy "Steve" is working at Walmart, and putting the ammo on the shelve. Before he does, he gets all his friends and family there, and the ammo is gone as soon as it gets there. I wouldn't be surprised if he's selling it on here, and reading this right now. 

So if anybody is wondering why they can never find ammo at Lake Geneva Walmart, now you know. Greed has gotten to the employees. Not sure if there's anything "illegal" or against the rules, but it sure pisses me off. I called and left a complaint. Anybody who buys ammo there, I suggest you do the same.

This gun was manufactured in 1918. These were manufactured from 1902 to 1929. It has a lanyard swivel on the left rear of the frame and is correct and a slide release, which was an improvement from the Model 1902 Sporting.

 The bore and the mechanics are excellent and the magazine has "CAL. 38 COLT" stamped on the bottom of the magazine, this is one of the nicer 1902's I have seen. This is a must have for anyone wanting a complete collection of the early Colt Automatics.

This is a Colt Model 1902 Military semi automatic pistol. It is .38 ACP caliber with a 6" barrel. The finish is a high polish blue with a case colored spur hammer and black hard rubber grips. This is in all original condition and I rate it at 95%. The gun is in excellent condition

I would like to buy, or trade for 22LR Lead nose Standard Velocity target ammo.  I prefer CCI, but will consider any match/target ammo that is similar or better.  I'm not looking to hoard or flip it, i just want to shoot it!

For trade I have .22 high velocity, .380, .40S&W (FMJ & JHP), .45, .223 (brass and steel), 5.56, and 12gague trap/skeet rounds

My rough conversions (pre-inflation):
I used to buy the 500 rnd bricks of CCI for $25 = .05 per bullet
The .380 I paid $30 for 100 so .30 per bullet = 6 to 1 conversion
The .40 I paid $20 for 50 so .40 per bullet = 8 to 1 conversion
The .223 steel I paid .30 per bullet so same as above
The .223 brass I paid .45 per bullet so 9 to 1
The 12g I paid $6 for 25 so .24 = 4.8 to 1
I am not selling, just trading.  The conversions are approximate (to the best of my memory) and open to negotiation
